      <div class="w-full max-w-[600px] mx-auto space-y-4">
        <HermannGridDemo isCard={false} />
        <div class="text-center text-xs text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400 italic">
          This illusion uses a fixed display for accuracy.
        </div>
        <!-- Controls panel for Dots Count Quiz -->
        <div class="w-full space-y-4 pt-2 flex flex-col items-center text-center">
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-between w-full p-4 bg-slate-900/60 border border-slate-800 rounded-xl text-xs gap-3">
            <div class="flex items-center space-x-2 w-full">
              <label for="dots-count-input" class="font-bold shrink-0 text-slate-300">How many dark dots do you see? </label>
              <input type="number" id="dots-count-input" class="w-20 bg-slate-950 border border-slate-700 text-center font-bold text-white rounded p-1" value="0" min="0" />
            </div>
            <button id="submit-dots-btn" class="bg-purple-600 hover:bg-purple-500 text-white font-bold px-4 py-2 rounded-lg shrink-0 transition-colors">Submit Guess</button>
          </div>
          
          <div id="dots-feedback-panel" class="hidden w-full text-left text-xs bg-slate-950/90 p-4 rounded-xl border border-slate-800 space-y-3">
            <h4 class="font-extrabold text-purple-400 text-sm border-b border-slate-800 pb-1.5 flex items-center justify-between">
              <span>Result Validation</span>
              <span id="dots-feedback-status" class="font-bold text-rose-500 font-mono">Incorrect ✗</span>
            </h4>
            <p class="text-slate-300 text-xs">
              Correct answer: <strong class="text-white">0</strong>. You guessed: <strong id="dots-user-guess" class="text-white">0</strong>.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-400 font-medium leading-relaxed">
              <strong>Why:</strong> The Hermann Grid exploits lateral inhibition. Visual receptors in your retina compete with neighboring cells (sensory receptive fields). Receptors processing line intersections receive surround inhibition from four sides, causing them to signal less brightness to the brain, producing illusionary gray spots. But physically, there are exactly 0 dark dots!
            </p>
            <button id="dots-try-again-btn" class="w-full bg-slate-800 hover:bg-slate-700 text-slate-300 font-bold py-2 rounded-lg text-xs border border-slate-700 shadow transition-all active:scale-95">Try Again</button>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Content Split Layout -->
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-12 pt-4">
      
      <!-- Left 2-Columns: Science and Prompt -->
      <div class="lg:col-span-2 space-y-10">
        <!-- EXPERIENCE IT FIRST prompt -->
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">🎮</span>
            <span>EXPERIENCE IT FIRST</span>
          </h2>
          <div class="bg-indigo-950/20 border-2 border-indigo-500/15 rounded-3xl p-6 text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            <p class="font-bold text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-200">Before reading the neuroscience explanation below, take a moment to interact with the demo above:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mt-3 space-y-2 text-xs sm:text-sm font-medium">
              <li>How does the visual change when you move your eyes or look at different parts of the screen?</li>
              <li>Use the slider or toggle buttons to reveal the actual geometric layout. Did it match what your eyes predicted?</li>
              <li>Pay attention to whether you can consciously force your brain to switch between interpretations.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- THE SCIENCE (400 words) -->
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">🧠</span>
            <span>THE SCIENCE</span>
          </h2>
          <div class="prose prose-indigo dark:prose-invert text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 leading-relaxed space-y-4 text-xs sm:text-sm font-semibold text-justify">
            <p>The Hermann Grid is a classic illusion that illustrates <strong>lateral inhibition</strong> in the retina. A grid of dark squares is separated by white lines. When you look at the grid, ghostly gray spots appear at the white intersections in your peripheral vision. However, if you stare directly at an intersection, the gray spot disappears.
    
    This occurs because of the receptive fields of retinal ganglion cells (center-surround organization). An intersection is surrounded by more light (four white lanes) than a straight lane segment (only two white lanes). As a result, the ganglion cells at the intersection receive more light in their inhibitory surround, causing them to fire less. This decreased firing is interpreted by the brain as less light, creating the perception of a gray spot. Staring directly at an intersection puts it in your fovea, where receptive fields are tiny and foveal cells do not suffer from this lateral inhibition, making the spot disappear.</p>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>

      <!-- Right Column: Fun Facts and Try This -->
      <div class="space-y-8">
        <!-- FUN FACTS -->
        <section class="rounded-3xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-slate-900/60 p-6 space-y-4 shadow-xl">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">💡</span>
            <span>FUN FACTS</span>
          </h3>
          <ul class="space-y-4 text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-300 font-semibold">
            
              <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
                <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
                <span>Discovered by German physiologist Ludimar Hermann in 1870 while reading a chemistry textbook.</span>
              </li>
            
              <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
                <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
                <span>The illusion is the classic textbook example of lateral inhibition and receptive field math in biology.</span>
              </li>
            
              <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
                <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
                <span>The gray spots only appear in your peripheral vision, disappearing as soon as you look directly at them.</span>
              </li>
            
              <li class="flex items-start space-x-2">
                <span class="text-purple-500 font-black">•</span>
                <span>The effect is reduced if you rotate the grid by 45 degrees, suggesting cortical orientation cells also play a role.</span>
              </li>
            
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- TRY THIS AT HOME -->
        <section class="rounded-3xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-slate-900/60 p-6 space-y-4 shadow-xl">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">🧪</span>
            <span>TRY THIS AT HOME</span>
          </h3>
          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-650 dark:text-slate-300 leading-relaxed font-semibold">
            Take a sheet of black paper. Use white chalk to draw a thick grid. Look at the intersections in your periphery. You will see gray spots flash at the crossings, showing lateral inhibition works on any high-contrast hand-drawn grid!
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- WHO DISCOVERED IT -->
        <section class="rounded-3xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-slate-900/60 p-6 space-y-4 shadow-xl">
          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white flex items-center space-x-2">
            <span class="text-purple-500">📜</span>
            <span>WHO DISCOVERED IT</span>
          </h3>
          <div class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-650 dark:text-slate-300 leading-relaxed font-semibold space-y-2">
            <p><strong>Discoverer:</strong> Ludimar Hermann (1870)</p>
            <p>Ludimar Hermann was reading a chemistry paper by John Tyndall that featured a grid of black figures. He noticed that gray spots kept flashing in his peripheral vision. He investigated this anomaly and published the findings, which became the foundation of retinal receptive field science.</p>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>

    </div>

    <!-- SEO content: 300 words naturally written -->
    <section class="border-t border-indigo-500/10 pt-12 space-y-4 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-black text-white uppercase tracking-wider text-center">Educational Resources & History</h3>
      <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-350 leading-relaxed text-justify font-semibold">
        Hermann Grid optical illusion lateral inhibition explanation. Discover retinal ganglion receptive fields, Ludimar Hermann's 1870 chemistry book discovery, and test our interactive grid-rounding SVG widget.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- RELATED ILLUSIONS -->
    <section class="border-t border-indigo-500/10 pt-12 space-y-6">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-black text-slate-900 dark:text-white text-center">Related Illusions</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        
      <a 
        href="/illusions/troxler-fading" 
        class="group rounded-xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-white dark:bg-slate-900/60 p-5 shadow-lg hover:border-purple-500/40 hover:-translate-y-1 hover:shadow-purple-500/10 transition-all duration-300"
      >
        <div class="text-[10px] font-bold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wide">Related Illusion</div>
        <h4 class="font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mt-1 group-hover:text-purple-400 transition-colors">
          Troxler Fading &rarr;
        </h4>
      </a>
    

      <a 
        href="/illusions/kanizsa-triangle" 
        class="group rounded-xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-white dark:bg-slate-900/60 p-5 shadow-lg hover:border-purple-500/40 hover:-translate-y-1 hover:shadow-purple-500/10 transition-all duration-300"
      >
        <div class="text-[10px] font-bold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wide">Related Illusion</div>
        <h4 class="font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mt-1 group-hover:text-purple-400 transition-colors">
          Kanizsa Triangle &rarr;
        </h4>
      </a>
    

      <a 
        href="/illusions/fraser-spiral" 
        class="group rounded-xl border border-indigo-950/20 bg-white dark:bg-slate-900/60 p-5 shadow-lg hover:border-purple-500/40 hover:-translate-y-1 hover:shadow-purple-500/10 transition-all duration-300"
      >
        <div class="text-[10px] font-bold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wide">Related Illusion</div>
        <h4 class="font-display text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white mt-1 group-hover:text-purple-400 transition-colors">
          Fraser Spiral &rarr;
        </h4>
      </a>
    
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>

  <script>
    // Share Page URL
    const sharePageBtn = document.getElementById('share-illusion-page-btn');
    const pageToast = document.getElementById('page-share-toast');

    sharePageBtn?.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const pageUrl = window.location.href;
      navigator.clipboard.writeText(pageUrl).then(() => {
        if (pageToast) {
          pageToast.classList.remove('opacity-0');
          pageToast.classList.add('opacity-100');
          setTimeout(() => {
            pageToast.classList.remove('opacity-100');
            pageToast.classList.add('opacity-0');
          }, 2000);
        }
      });
    });

    // Handle Global Speed Mult
    const checkSpeed = () => {
      const level = localStorage.getItem('speed-multiplier-level') || '5';
      let multiplier = 1.0;
      const parsed = parseInt(level);
      if (parsed <= 5) {
        multiplier = 0.2 + (parsed - 1) * 0.2;
      } else {
        multiplier = 1.0 + (parsed - 5) * 0.4;
      }
      document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--speed-multiplier', multiplier.toString());
    };
    checkSpeed();
    window.addEventListener('storage', checkSpeed);
  </script>
</Layout>
